"1585":"1585","1530":"1530","1552":"1552","about 1502":"about 1502","1485":"1485","about 1488":"about 1488","3 February 1553":"3 February 1553","1549":"1549","Hartsop Hall, Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","Lowther, Westmorland, England":"Lowther, Westmorland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lowther","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Cumbria, so called from the river on which it stands. The placename is of obscure etymology, perhaps of ancient Welsh origin (compare   Lauder  ), or from Old Norse <i>lauthr</i> ‘froth, foam’ + <i>á</i> ‘river’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lawther","meanings":["Scottish, northern Irish, and northern English: variant of   Lowther   and   Lauder  ."]},{"name":"Lauder","meanings":["Scottish (Borders): habitational name from Lauder in Berwickshire, originally a name for the river Leader (itself from British <i>lou-</i> + <i>dubro-</i> ‘cleansing river’). Compare   Lauderdale  ."]},{"name":"Lattea","meanings":["Altered form of English   Lowther  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":61,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":70,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":97,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":99,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Lowther was born about 1488, in Lowther, Westmorland, England, his father, Hugh Lowther, was 28 and his mother, Ann Threlkeld, was 39. He married Lucy Curwen about 1502. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1488–":"umbes 1488–Surnud","1479–1482":"1479–1482","1481–1552":"1481–1552","1483–1484":"1483–1484","1484–1524":"1484–1524","1485–1552":"1485–1552","1488–Male":"1488–Surnud","1488–1530":"1488–1530","1510–1555":"1510–1555","1461–1510":"1461–1510","1451–Female":"1451–Surnud","1451":"1451","1484":"1484","1461":"1461","1483":"1483","1482":"1482","1481":"1481","1558":"1558","1524":"1524","1479":"1479","1555":"1555","1510":"1510","1587":"1587","1488":"1488","1585":"1585","1530":"1530","1552":"1552","about